# WHAT IS logrusorgru/aurora AND WHY IS IT THE 57TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# aurora (https://github.com/logrusorgru/aurora, 1500+ stars) is
# **Konstantin Ivanov's "ultimate ANSI colors for Golang"** —
# a chainable-method ANSI colorizer released 2017 as an
# alternative to fatih/color.  Where fatih/color uses
# imperative `color.New(color.FgRed).Println(...)` style,
# aurora uses CHAINABLE METHODS via a Value interface that
# every colored value implements.
#
# aurora's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. CHAINABLE METHOD API — Every aurora coloring function
#      returns a Value that implements `aurora.Value`
#      interface — chainable via methods or wrappable in
#      other coloring calls:
#
#          import . "github.com/logrusorgru/aurora"
#
#          fmt.Println(Bold(Red("error")))
#          fmt.Println(Red("error").Bold())              // same result
#          fmt.Println(Red("error").Bold().BgYellow())
#
#          fmt.Println(BgBrightBlue(White("Title").Bold()))
#
#          // Iterator-style multi-color:
#          for i, line := range lines {
#              color := Sprintf(Index(uint8(i), "%s"), line)
#              fmt.Println(color)
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * fatih/color: imperative `color.New(...).Println(...)`
#                         or `color.RedString("...")`
#         * lipgloss: declarative style structs
#         * gookit/color: multiple APIs in one library
#         * aurora: CHAINABLE methods returning Value interface
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with chainable Value-returning
#      methods.
#
#   2. VALUE INTERFACE FOR fmt-COMPATIBILITY — aurora's Value
#      interface implements fmt.Stringer + fmt.Formatter,
#      meaning colored values work TRANSPARENTLY in fmt.Sprintf,
#      fmt.Printf, fmt.Errorf, log.Printf, etc:
#
#          fmt.Printf("%s: %s\n", Yellow("WARN"), message)
#          fmt.Sprintf("user=%s id=%d", Bold(name), id)
#          log.Printf("HTTP %s %s", Cyan(method), url)
#
#      The colors are applied via Format() method when the
#      Value is rendered.  No special function calls needed
#      to mix colored + uncolored content.  Compare:
#         * fatih/color: `color.Sprintf` or wrapping
#                         color.RedString in Sprintf
#         * lipgloss: explicit `.Render()` calls
#         * gookit/color: HTML-tag syntax in format strings
#         * aurora: SEAMLESS fmt-package compatibility via
#                    Value interface
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with seamless fmt-package
#      interop via fmt.Formatter implementation.
#
#   3. 24-BIT RGB + INDEXED COLOR — aurora supports the full
#      ANSI color spectrum:
#         - 8 basic colors (Red, Green, Blue, ...)
#         - 8 bright variants (BrightRed, BrightGreen, ...)
#         - 16 background variants (BgRed, BgGreen, ...)
#         - 256-color palette via Index(n, text)
#         - 24-bit RGB via Sprintf with custom color escapes
#         - Foreground + background combinations
#         - Bold, Italic, Underline, Faint, Reverse, Blink,
#           Conceal, CrossedOut, Framed, Encircled,
#           Overlined modifiers
#
#      Compare:
#         * fatih/color: 16-color + basic modifiers
#         * lipgloss: full RGB + via termenv
#         * gookit/color: 16/256/RGB
#         * aurora: 16/256/RGB + extensive modifiers
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with comprehensive
#      modifier support (Framed, Encircled, Overlined).
#
#   4. DOT-IMPORT-STYLE TYPICAL USAGE — aurora is designed to
#      be DOT-IMPORTED for terse syntax:
#
#          import . "github.com/logrusorgru/aurora"
#
#          // Now Red, Bold, BgYellow etc are bare names in scope:
#          fmt.Println(Red("error").Bold())
#          fmt.Println(BgYellow(Black("warning")))
#
#      The Go community generally discourages dot-imports for
#      code clarity, but aurora's API was designed assuming
#      dot-import for ergonomics.  Compare:
#         * fatih/color: `color.Red(...)` package-qualified
#         * lipgloss: `lipgloss.NewStyle()` package-qualified
#         * gookit/color: `color.Red.Sprint(...)`
#         * aurora: dot-import for `Red("...").Bold()`
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with dot-import-friendly
#      API design.
#
#   5. WTF/NAABU-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — aurora is used by:
#         * wtfutil/wtf (19000+ stars terminal dashboard) —
#           uses aurora for status colors across 60+ widgets
#         * projectdiscovery/naabu (port scanner) — uses aurora
#           for terminal status output (Project Discovery
#           security tools — same family as goflags R563)
#         * traefik (cloud-native reverse proxy) — early
#           versions used aurora
#         * imgdiff (THIS — image diff tool)
#         * swartzrock/ecsview (AWS ECS terminal viewer)
#         * Many security-tools + monitoring-dashboards Go
#           binaries
#      Compare:
#         * fatih/color: general-purpose adoption
#         * gookit/color: Chinese-developer ecosystem
#         * lipgloss: Charm ecosystem
#         * aurora: Project Discovery security + wtf terminal-
#                    dashboard ecosystems
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with security-tools-and-
#      dashboard-ecosystem provenance.
#
# aurora's relationship to other documented Go libraries:
#
#   * Like fatih/color — both provide terminal color output
#   * Unlike fatih/color — chainable Value-returning methods
#                          + fmt.Formatter interop vs imperative
#                          color.New(...).Println(...)
#   * Like gookit/color — both have chainable methods
#   * Unlike gookit/color — no HTML-tag-syntax; fmt-compatible
#                            Value interface instead
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust: owo-colors (R526) — chainable colorizer with
#                  similar Value semantics
#         * TS-Node: chalk — chainable colors with Proxy-trap
#                    method chaining
#         * Python: click.style + colorama — similar function-call
#                    approach
#     aurora is the FIRST documented Go colorizer with
#     fmt-package transparent Value interface + chainable
#     methods + dot-import-friendly API.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE imgdiff CLI — alexflint/go-arg + aurora
#
# imgdiff's CLI in cmd/main.go uses alexflint/go-arg for argv
# parsing (already documented) + aurora for colored output:
#
#     import (
#         "github.com/n7olkachev/imgdiff/pkg/imgdiff"
#         "github.com/alexflint/go-arg"
#         . "github.com/logrusorgru/aurora"
#     )
#
#     func main() {
#         var args struct {
#             Threshold    float64 `arg:"-t,--threshold" help:"Color difference threshold" default:"0.1"`
#             DiffImage    bool    `arg:"--diff-image" help:"Render image to diff output" default:"false"`
#             FailOnLayout bool    `arg:"--fail-on-layout" help:"Exit if images have different layout" default:"false"`
#             Base    string `arg:"positional" help:"Base image."`
#             Compare string `arg:"positional" help:"Image to compare with."`
#             Output  string `arg:"positional" help:"Output image path."`
#         }
#         arg.MustParse(&args)
#         // ...
#         if args.FailOnLayout && !image1.Bounds().Eq(image2.Bounds()) {
#             fmt.Println(Red("Failure!").Bold(),
#                         "Images have different layout.")
#             os.Exit(2)
#         }
#         result := imgdiff.Diff(image1, image2, &imgdiff.Options{
#             Threshold: args.Threshold,
#             DiffImage: args.DiffImage,
#         })
#         // ...
#     }
#
# Usage:
#   imgdiff [flags] <base-image> <compare-image> <output-image>
#
# Positional arguments:
#   <base-image>      Base image to compare against
#   <compare-image>   Image to compare with base
#   <output-image>    Output diff image path
#
# Flags:
#   -t, --threshold <0..1>  Color difference threshold (0.1 default)
#   --diff-image            Render image to diff output (instead of
#                            transparent background)
#   --fail-on-layout        Exit code 2 if image layouts differ
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Go colorizer:
#
#   1. CHAINABLE Value-RETURNING METHODS — Every other documented
#      Go colorizer uses imperative function calls (fatih/color),
#      declarative style structs (lipgloss), or HTML tags
#      (gookit/color).  aurora returns a Value interface chainable
#      via methods.
#
#   2. fmt.Formatter VALUE INTERFACE — Every other documented Go
#      colorizer requires explicit render/sprint calls. aurora's
#      Value interface implements fmt.Formatter for seamless
#      fmt.Printf/Sprintf/Errorf integration.
#
#   3. COMPREHENSIVE MODIFIER SUPPORT — Every other documented
#      Go colorizer focuses on color.  aurora adds Framed,
#      Encircled, Overlined, Conceal, CrossedOut modifiers.
#
#   4. DOT-IMPORT-FRIENDLY API — Every other documented Go
#      colorizer is package-qualified-by-default.  aurora's
#      API is designed for dot-import (Bold, Red, BgYellow as
#      bare names).
#
#   5. PROJECT-DISCOVERY + WTF-DASHBOARD ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE —
#      Every other documented Go colorizer has different
#      provenance.  aurora is the colorizer for wtfutil/wtf
#      (19k+ stars dashboard) + Project Discovery security
#      tools (naabu/etc) + imgdiff + ecsview.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/n7olkachev/imgdiff/blob/main/cmd/main.go
# `var args struct` go-arg tag attributes.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version]' \
    '(-t --threshold)'{-t+,--threshold=}'[color difference threshold (default 0.1)]:N (0..1):' \
    '--diff-image[render image to diff output (vs transparent bg)]' \
    '--fail-on-layout[exit code 2 if image layouts differ]' \
    '1:base image:_files -g "*.(png|jpg|jpeg|gif|webp)"' \
    '2:image to compare:_files -g "*.(png|jpg|jpeg|gif|webp)"' \
    '3:output diff image:_files' \
    && ret=0

return ret
